  </header>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="wrap hero-inner">
      <div class="hero-kicker">Follow up brief</div>
      <h1>You already run SFSP. This builds on that.</h1>
      <p>
        During the school year, families rely on these meals. In the summer, access becomes the challenge.
      </p>
      <p>
        You already have the experience, approvals, and relationships in place.
      </p>
      <p>
        Rural non-congregate adds a layer of coordination — delivery, enrollment, and documentation all need to work together throughout the season. That’s where programs tend to get complicated.
      </p>
      <p>
        RuralBites is here to support that coordination.
      </p>
      <p>
        We work alongside your team to bring those pieces into one flow so the program can run consistently without adding strain on staff.
      </p>
      <p>
        Meals still come from your approved vendors. Your team stays in control. This model simply extends how you reach families who can’t consistently access a site.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section white">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="label">What RuralBites helps manage</div>
      <h2>Built to support the practical side of increasing summer meal access</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        RuralBites is designed to help sponsors and communities support families who need summer meals at home, without asking teams to add staff or build brand new systems from scratch.
      </p>
      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:14px;">
        This model is designed to align with USDA non-congregate guidance and support the documentation sponsors need to manage the program with confidence.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">📝</div>
          <h3>Flexible family sign up</h3>
          <p>
            Families can sign up in the way that works best for them — online or through a mobile friendly experience — making it easier to participate and easier for your team to manage.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">🚚</div>
          <h3>Meal delivery support</h3>
          <p>
            Help coordinate getting meals from preparation sites to families across your community in a way that is organized and manageable.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">📂</div>
          <h3>Service records and reporting support</h3>
          <p>
            Keep meal service and delivery records organized so reporting and oversight feel clear and manageable throughout the summer.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="spotlight">
        <h3>Designed to support your team</h3>
        <p>
          This is not about adding complexity. It is about making delivery and service support easier to manage within the structure you already have.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section light">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="label">What this could look like for Roosevelt</div>
      <h2>A model designed around your geography and your community</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        This is where RuralBites becomes practical. Not as an abstract platform, but as a support system shaped around how Roosevelt School District 66 could increase access for families during the summer in a way that feels manageable and community centered.
      </p>

      <div class="list-card">
        <h3>For Roosevelt School District 66, this could mean</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Household level delivery support across the district</li>
          <li>Easier ways for families to sign up and participate</li>
          <li>Clearer service records and reporting support</li>
          <li>A more manageable path to reaching families beyond a single site</li>
          <li>A system that supports your team without asking you to rebuild from scratch</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section white">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="label">When this works well</div>
      <h2>This tends to work well when</h2>

      <div class="list-card">
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Families are spread out across distance</li>
          <li>Some households cannot consistently get to a site</li>
          <li>Your team wants to expand access without expanding staffing</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section light">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="label">What this looks like week to week</div>
      <h2>How the program runs week to week</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        This is meant to fit within your program — not create a second job for your staff. The goal is to make weekly operations feel clear, repeatable, and manageable.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">1</div>
          <h3>Families sign up</h3>
          <p>Families enroll and are organized by household.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">2</div>
          <h3>Meals are coordinated</h3>
          <p>Meals are coordinated across vendors and delivery.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <div class="icon">3</div>
          <h3>Service is recorded</h3>
          <p>Service is recorded as the program runs.</p>
        </div>
